"Rodríguez-Trelles F., Rodríguez M.A.","Rapid micro-evolution and loss of chromosomal diversity in Drosophila in response to climate warming",1998,"Evolutionary Ecology","12","7",,"829","838",,,10.1023/A:1006546616462,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0031794207&partnerID=40&md5=aab9e2d937e9360fa842e70357b9a7fb","Dept. of Ecol. and Evol. Biology, University of California-Irvine, Irvine, CA 92697, United States; Depto. de Genet. i de Microbiologia, Unitat de Genetica, Universitat Autonoma de Barcelona, 08193 Bellaterra (Barcelona), Spain; Area de Ecología, Facultad de Ciencias, Univ. de Alcalá de Henares, 28871 Alcala de Henares (Madrid), Spain","Rodríguez-Trelles, F., Dept. of Ecol. and Evol. Biology, University of California-Irvine, Irvine, CA 92697, United States, Depto. de Genet. i de Microbiologia, Unitat de Genetica, Universitat Autonoma de Barcelona, 08193 Bellaterra (Barcelona), Spain; Rodríguez, M.A., Dept. of Ecol. and Evol. Biology, University of California-Irvine, Irvine, CA 92697, United States, Area de Ecología, Facultad de Ciencias, Univ. de Alcalá de Henares, 28871 Alcala de Henares (Madrid), Spain","Concern regarding the ecological impact of rapid global warming has encouraged research on climate-induced changes in biological systems. Critical problems, still poorly understood, are the potential for rapid adaptive responses and their genetic costs to populations. The O chromosomal polymorphisms of Drosophila subobscura have been monitored at a southern Palearctic locality experiencing sustained climate warming since the mid-1970s. Observations suggest that the population is rapidly evolving in response to the new environmental conditions, and has lost a significant amount of chromosomal diversity (18.3% in 16 years). These findings are consistent with results from another population of D. subobscura, which is also undergoing climate warming, and are in accord with what would be expected from latitudinal and seasonal patterns of the various inversions. In addition, data on the O chromosomal polymorphisms from other localities throughout the range of this species suggest that other populations vary similarly.","Biodiversity; Chromosomal polymorphism; Climate change; Drosophila subobscura; Micro-evolution","climate change; evolutionary biology; genetic variation; global warming; Diptera; Drosophila subobscura; Drosophilidae",,,,,,"Anderson, W.W., Arnold, J., Baldwin, D.G., Beckenbach, A.T., Brown, C.J., Bryant, S.H., Coyne, J.A., Moore, J.A., Four decades of inversion polymorphism in Drosophila pseudoobscura (1991) Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. USA, 88, pp. 10367-10371; Bennett, A.F., Dao, K.M., Lenski, R.L., Rapid evolution in response to high-temperature selection (1990) Nature, 346, pp. 79-81; Bulmer, M.G., (1980) The Mathematical Theory of Quantitative Genetics, , Clarendon Press, Oxford; Carson, H.L., Variation in genetic recombination in natural populations (1955) J. Cell. Comp. Physiol., 45 (2 SUPPL.), pp. 221-236; Dobzhansky, T.H., A response of certain gene arrangements in the third chromosome of Drosophila pseudoobscura to natural selection (1947) Genetics, 32, pp. 142-160; Fontdevila, A., Zapata, C., Álvarez, G., Sánchez, L., Méndez, J., Enríquez, J., Genetic coadaptation in the chromosomal polymorphism of Drosophila subobscura. I. Seasonal changes of gametic disequilibrium in a natural population (1983) Genétics, 105, pp. 935-955; Gosteli, M., Chromosomal polymorphism in natural populations of Drosophila subobscura near Zürich, Switzerland: A contribution to long-term comparisons (1990) Genética, 81, pp. 199-204; Gosteli, M., Differential flight activity among karyotypes: Daily and weather induced changes in chromosomal inversion polymorphism in natural populations of Drosophila subobscura (1991) Genética, 84, pp. 129-136; Holt, R.D., The microevolutionary consequences of climate change (1990) Tree, 5, pp. 311-315; Johannessen, O.M., Bjørgo, E., Miles, M.W., Global warming and the Arctic (19